properties.name: East Bluff Trail
properties.Description: A moderately ascending/descending trail in the woods â€“ no view of the lake.

properties.name: Balanced Rock Trail
properties.Description: Steep climbing trail more like an uneven rocky staircase. Balanced rock is 3/4 way up, about 100 feet off the trail. Many scenic views.

properties.name: East Bluff Woods Trail
properties.Description: A trail with periodic stone steps ascending; the most gradual way up the bluff (but still gains 500 feet elevation). All in the woods with scenic vistas of the lake. Elephant Rock and Elephant Cave along the way.

properties.name: Tumbled Rocks Trail
properties.Description: The park's most popular trail follows along the lakeshore winding through the boulder/talus fields at the base of the west bluff. Great scenic views from lake level.

properties.name: West Bluff Trail
properties.Description: Trail with numerous but moderate ups and downs with scenic views of the lake from atop the West Bluff; many stone steps at the north end and a steep ascent at the south end.

properties.name: Sauk Point Trail
properties.Description: Wooded and grassy ridge, farm, meadow, woods trail that traverses the highest point in the Baraboo Hills.

properties.name: Rozno's Meadow Trail
properties.Description: The park's newest trail, an easy grassy walk through a prairie restoration project in the valley with a great view of a glacial terminal moraine, then ascends/descends through the woods to join the Uplands trail.

properties.name: CCC Trail
properties.Description: Steep climbing trails with stone steps. From the Group Camp to the top of the bluff.

properties.name: Group Camp Trail
properties.Description: Foot path leading from outdoor group camp to the south shore picnic and beach area. Some steps along the way.

properties.name: Grottos Trail
properties.Description: A level gravel trail running along the south face of the East Bluff.

properties.name: Potholes Trail
properties.Description: Steep climbing trail with stone steps passing narrowly between quartzite rock faces. Wooded near bottom, with ancient rounded eroded potholes near the top, formed by swirling water.
